n an urban river in southwestern Ontario, and a portrayal of the complex underwater world of the South Pacific. Travelling the River Ganges in India, the author finds that a massive misuse of water is complicated by a billion people’s faith-based adoration of the same water. The Memory of Water probes a crucial and contemporary issue—that of our relationship to water and the wildlife and human life that depends upon it. This book will appeal to anyone interested in the natural world, in artistic depictions of it, or in a good story well told.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnimal-water relationships. 0aWater and civilization. 4aArt. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLife Writing. 4aTravel. 7aNATURE / Ecosystems & Habitats / Polar Regions.2bisacsh  aarctic.  aart.  abaffin island.  acanoing.  ageorgian bay.  akayaking.  alakes.  alife writing.  aoceans.  apainting.  apolar expedition.  arivers.  astreams.  awater.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458876340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554588763423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554588763/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles